22
00:29:07,040 --> 00:29:07,840
biology of genomes.

23
00:29:07,940 --> 00:29:10,960
We have lots of discussion of
variation graphs and genome graphs.

24
00:29:11,260 --> 00:29:15,840
I want to point out that these graph
models here where you have genomes

25
00:29:15,840 --> 00:29:19,640
walking through nodes, which represent
sequence, these are effectively

26
00:29:19,640 --> 00:29:22,780
equivalent to alignments
between the genomes.

27
00:29:22,820 --> 00:29:23,520
And they're the same.

28
00:29:23,520 --> 00:29:24,680
It's just a different
way of thinking of them.

29
00:29:25,060 --> 00:29:27,680
Actually, in this talk, we'll be
looking a lot more at this particular

30
00:29:27,680 --> 00:29:31,380
representation because it's more
scalable, more flexible, and it lets us

31
00:29:31,380 --> 00:29:33,540
go after these questions
for the first time.

32
00:29:34,930 --> 00:29:38,390
In the first version of the Human
Pangenome project, also this has been

33
00:29:38,390 --> 00:29:42,250
discussed a number of times, but we built

34
00:29:43,110 --> 00:29:45,310
these chromosomes independently.

35
00:29:46,070 --> 00:29:49,150
And so we would take some collection
of contigs we think go to a

36
00:29:49,150 --> 00:29:52,450
certain chromosome, put them together
in the pangenome graph builder or a

37
00:29:52,450 --> 00:29:56,010
mini graph cactus, and we would
build a graph out of them.

38
00:29:56,110 --> 00:29:57,530
So we get these isolated components.

39
00:29:57,970 --> 00:30:01,970
But what we discovered by experimentation
was that if we put together

40
00:30:01,970 --> 00:30:05,530
acrocentric chromosomes, we would
observe that they form a single

41
00:30:05,530 --> 00:30:06,230
component.

42
00:30:06,230 --> 00:30:09,390
And actually, the tightest part
of this component where they come

43
00:30:09,390 --> 00:30:12,770
together, this is the pseudo homologous
region on the short arms of the

44
00:30:12,770 --> 00:30:14,110
acrocentrics that's been discussed.

45
00:30:14,410 --> 00:30:19,250
And that is the cause of recurrent
Robertsonian translocations in

46
00:30:19,250 --> 00:30:19,950
humans.

47
00:30:19,950 --> 00:30:21,170
So we needed to see this.

48
00:30:21,170 --> 00:30:24,530
But technical reasons led
us to break them apart.

49
00:30:24,790 --> 00:30:27,890
And so what we wanted to do in the
second iteration of the Pangenome

50
00:30:27,890 --> 00:30:30,310
project was to put all of
these genomes together.

51
00:30:31,320 --> 00:30:35,880
And to do that, we couldn't build
a single graph reliably because of

52
00:30:35,880 --> 00:30:39,000
computational constraints,
reliability of just the process.

53
00:30:39,300 --> 00:30:42,820
And so we turned to a concept
called the implicit data structure.

54
00:30:43,100 --> 00:30:47,280
So here, the foundation of all this
is an implicit interval tree that

55
00:30:47,280 --> 00:30:50,480
lets us query from a target range,

56
00:30:52,040 --> 00:30:55,880
or any genome range, find ranges
of other things that overlap it.

57
00:30:56,120 --> 00:30:58,340
And so we would typically
write that in a tree.

58
00:30:58,740 --> 00:31:01,060
But this is very big and
heavy, and you don't have to.

59
00:31:01,140 --> 00:31:06,000
You can simulate the tree just by
sorting the intervals and doing binary

60
00:31:06,000 --> 00:31:06,700
search over them.

61
00:31:06,880 --> 00:31:09,920
And so this implicit model is actually
the foundation of how we go and

62
00:31:09,920 --> 00:31:13,180
look through the alignments
to then look at the graph.

63
00:31:13,400 --> 00:31:18,080
And so we effectively simulate a
graph by building this many-way

64
00:31:18,080 --> 00:31:18,780
alignment.

65
00:31:18,780 --> 00:31:22,540
We use a tool called WFMASH,
which is a variant of MASHMAP that

66
00:31:22,540 --> 00:31:24,360
actually gets base-level
alignments out of it.

67
00:31:24,700 --> 00:31:29,440
And then we just compress and
index all of the path files, the

68
00:31:29,440 --> 00:31:32,280
pairwise alignment files that come
out, effectively making a kind of

69
00:31:32,280 --> 00:31:33,720
interval forest over all of them.

70
00:31:33,800 --> 00:31:37,440
And let's answer the question at
every part of any genome in the entire

71
00:31:37,440 --> 00:31:39,660
set, what other genomes align there?

72
00:31:39,760 --> 00:31:42,780
And we can do, effectively,
liftover across the whole set.

73
00:31:42,980 --> 00:31:46,120
And if we want, we can render an
actual graph out of it if needed.

74
00:31:48,280 --> 00:31:51,760
So you get this by doing
an all-to-all alignment.

75
00:31:51,760 --> 00:31:53,860
And that's a pretty gnarly thing.

76
00:31:53,980 --> 00:31:58,700
So if you really did it exhaustively
on these genomes, it's 465 or

77
00:31:58,700 --> 00:32:00,460
466 if you count GRCh38,

78
00:32:01,260 --> 00:32:05,020
you have a two septillion
cell matrix, right?

79
00:32:05,100 --> 00:32:07,260
And that is clearly intractable.

80
00:32:07,540 --> 00:32:11,060
And in order to avoid the quadratic
pollution that this would imply,

81
00:32:11,360 --> 00:32:16,350
this is, by the way, bane of Memphis
XAI, which is burning a bunch of

82
00:32:16,350 --> 00:32:20,090
methane to make quadratic
deep learning models work,

83
00:32:20,870 --> 00:32:22,950
you can exploit a number of things.

84
00:32:23,090 --> 00:32:26,210
So one is that the whole genome
alignment, it's very sparse.

85
00:32:26,330 --> 00:32:29,270
So you don't actually have to do
complete alignment of every cell.

86
00:32:29,490 --> 00:32:32,050
You already know how to do that
because you can use miniMAP2.

87
00:32:32,530 --> 00:32:36,030
But panmixia means that most of the
possible pairwise alignments are

88
00:32:36,030 --> 00:32:38,750
redundant because most of the genomes
are kind of similar to each other.

89
00:32:39,030 --> 00:32:40,670
That means we don't have to do all pairs.

90
00:32:40,850 --> 00:32:42,870
We can do some subset of them.

91
00:32:43,810 --> 00:32:48,430
And so the idea is that we look
at everything transitively.

92
00:32:48,430 --> 00:32:52,170
This shows a random graph where
we have the components colored in

93
00:32:52,170 --> 00:32:54,870
different colors and we have the
fraction of the edges that we combine

94
00:32:54,870 --> 00:32:57,930
between the 500 nodes
here shown as this P.

95
00:32:58,130 --> 00:33:00,630
So one-tenth of one percent,
we have a lot of components.

96
00:33:00,910 --> 00:33:03,690
If we were to look from any genome
to every other one, we wouldn't

97
00:33:03,690 --> 00:33:04,390
make connections.

98
00:33:04,630 --> 00:33:09,470
But as we increase this, we
achieve a single component very

99
00:33:09,470 --> 00:33:11,970
reliably at just a fraction
of the total alignment set.

100
00:33:12,150 --> 00:33:13,010
And so that's what we did.

101
00:33:13,850 --> 00:33:18,770
So we aligned about 11 and a half
percent of all the haplotype pairs

102
00:33:18,770 --> 00:33:19,470
to each other.

103
00:33:19,830 --> 00:33:21,790
It's hundreds of thousands of alignments.

104
00:33:22,290 --> 00:33:25,170
Well, not hundreds of thousands of
alignments, but I think about 25,000.

105
00:33:25,590 --> 00:33:28,190
This is hundreds of times the
critical threshold to make a single

106
00:33:28,190 --> 00:33:28,890
component.

107
00:33:28,890 --> 00:33:32,610
And so we're basically guaranteed
to kind of simulate the full graph

108
00:33:32,610 --> 00:33:33,570
without having to build it.

109
00:33:34,470 --> 00:33:39,230
And as a QC of this, we can query
across a reference and just ask, do

110
00:33:39,230 --> 00:33:40,730
we see all the other genomes here?

111
00:33:40,890 --> 00:33:45,530
And in this panmictic population,
where all the chromosomes are basically

112
00:33:45,530 --> 00:33:48,890
homologous to each other, you
effectively hope that in every megabase

113
00:33:48,890 --> 00:33:52,350
pair of every chromosome, you
see all the other genomes.

114
00:33:52,410 --> 00:33:53,870
And that's true.

115
00:33:54,010 --> 00:33:58,850
The notable exceptions being ribosomal
DNA, some centromere regions,

116
00:33:59,070 --> 00:34:01,670
and the sex chromosomes, where
you expect different copying.

117
00:34:02,420 --> 00:34:03,280
So that's good.

118
00:34:03,740 --> 00:34:04,520
Suggest it worked.

119
00:34:04,740 --> 00:34:09,440
And then we wanted to understand
what else we can see.

120
00:34:09,600 --> 00:34:12,980
We wanted to build this single graph
so we could see, is there anything

121
00:34:12,980 --> 00:34:15,000
else like the acrocentrics?

122
00:34:15,000 --> 00:34:19,560
And this is a heat map that shows us
at every position, it's every 100

123
00:34:19,560 --> 00:34:24,480
KB window in CHM13, how many other
chromosomes do we see in these

124
00:34:24,480 --> 00:34:25,180
alignments?

125
00:34:25,180 --> 00:34:29,180
Not just CHM13 itself, but we've
been able to label all of the HPRC

126
00:34:29,180 --> 00:34:31,860
assemblies and we can see
which ones we see in that set.

127
00:34:32,020 --> 00:34:36,220
And you'll notice that the acrocentrics
very clearly show up, so we'll

128
00:34:36,220 --> 00:34:37,760
be able to have a positive control there.

129
00:34:38,240 --> 00:34:41,120
You'll also see the pseudo-autosomal
region, although I believe it's

130
00:34:41,120 --> 00:34:43,920
masked on the version of Y that
we're using, so it might be a little

131
00:34:43,920 --> 00:34:44,620
confusing.

132
00:34:44,620 --> 00:34:47,860
But the thing that's important for
this talk is that at the end of

133
00:34:47,860 --> 00:34:50,760
almost all chromosomes,
you'll see this peak.

134
00:34:51,300 --> 00:34:55,120
And if you zoom in on a few, you
see that it's not just a generic

135
00:34:55,120 --> 00:34:55,820
thing.

136
00:34:55,820 --> 00:34:58,520
And by the way, we're masking
and ignoring telomeres here.

137
00:34:58,680 --> 00:35:02,500
So we're looking just at the
unique sequence of the chromosome.

138
00:35:03,020 --> 00:35:06,000
It's actually not so unique in many
cases, shared between different

139
00:35:06,000 --> 00:35:06,700
chromosomes.

140
00:35:06,800 --> 00:35:09,020
This is the acrocentric arms, right?

141
00:35:09,160 --> 00:35:11,520
This is chromosome 1, chromosome 4.

142
00:35:11,800 --> 00:35:14,500
So there's a particular kind of
pattern that's unique to every one of

143
00:35:14,500 --> 00:35:16,900
the chromosome ends, a
set of relationships.

144
00:35:17,220 --> 00:35:19,580
And so then the next step
is to try to understand

145
00:35:20,840 --> 00:35:22,000
first the scale of that,

146
00:35:22,640 --> 00:35:25,060
and then how are the
relationships working out.

147
00:35:25,240 --> 00:35:29,630
So this is an attempt to
understand how big these

148
00:35:29,630 --> 00:35:31,870
putative pseudo-homologous regions are.

149
00:35:32,030 --> 00:35:34,710
These are regions that look like they're
recombining between different non-

150
00:35:34,710 --> 00:35:35,450
homologous chromosomes.

151
00:35:35,950 --> 00:35:40,950
We do this by going to the bundle,
collection of every set of HPRC

152
00:35:40,950 --> 00:35:45,130
assemblies and every chromosome, and
we walk in from the telomere until

153
00:35:45,130 --> 00:35:48,710
we stop seeing other chromosomes
in the implicit graph.

154
00:35:49,150 --> 00:35:53,730
And at that point, we're on
just the chromosome origin, and

155
00:35:53,730 --> 00:35:57,130
effectively we're marking on
this plot where that happens.

156
00:35:57,350 --> 00:36:02,310
And so you see that on XY acrocentric
short arms, we go over the

157
00:36:02,310 --> 00:36:04,530
500 kb that we were
considering in this study.

158
00:36:05,030 --> 00:36:08,990
Par 2 is in the 300 kb
range, so we confirm that.

159
00:36:09,510 --> 00:36:13,730
But you'll notice that you have a
distribution of lengths in the tens

160
00:36:13,730 --> 00:36:18,410
to hundreds of kb kilobase pairs across
almost all the chromosomes, with

161
00:36:18,410 --> 00:36:19,110
a few exceptions.

162
00:36:19,330 --> 00:36:21,850
One, two, three, four, five,
yeah, seven exceptions.

163
00:36:22,350 --> 00:36:25,150
We note they don't seem to be
mixing like the other ones.

164
00:36:25,870 --> 00:36:30,350
And so, of course, we're going to
build a graph to see this, and yeah,

165
00:36:31,100 --> 00:36:34,100
so then we orbited this hairball
for a minute and decided we couldn't

166
00:36:34,100 --> 00:36:37,520
understand anything that was
going on in here directly.

167
00:36:37,640 --> 00:36:41,040
This is not as clear as the combination
of acrocentrics that we saw,

168
00:36:41,560 --> 00:36:44,600
but it does make one
component, which is nice.

169
00:36:45,240 --> 00:36:49,300
And to understand what's going on
inside of it, we're going to untangle

170
00:36:49,300 --> 00:36:50,460
it in some sense.

171
00:36:50,580 --> 00:36:54,300
We're going to take bundles of
the contigs from each one of the

172
00:36:54,300 --> 00:36:56,640
chromosomes and then
compare them to each other.

173
00:36:56,840 --> 00:37:01,340
And so we have this bundle, for
example, from chromosome 8q, and we can

174
00:37:01,340 --> 00:37:04,620
compare it to chromosome 10q
within the space of this graph

175
00:37:05,220 --> 00:37:09,760
by effectively thinking about the
overlap of those two bundles, like how

176
00:37:09,760 --> 00:37:13,680
much of the overlap we use a Jaccard
metric, which is asking how many

177
00:37:13,680 --> 00:37:17,380
base pairs on the intersection of
those two versus the union of them.

178
00:37:18,060 --> 00:37:20,640
So that gives us this way of
looking at the interchromosomal

179
00:37:20,640 --> 00:37:22,320
relationships that's actually pangenomic.

180
00:37:22,420 --> 00:37:24,060
It's considering the whole set of genomes.

181
00:37:26,110 --> 00:37:30,590
Yielding, and that yields this heat
map, actually, which is, we have

182
00:37:30,590 --> 00:37:33,710
this kind of phylogenetic relationship,
which we're, this is just for

183
00:37:33,710 --> 00:37:34,410
grouping.

184
00:37:34,410 --> 00:37:37,350
We don't really know or think
directly that there is a phylogenetic

185
00:37:37,350 --> 00:37:39,510
relationship between
the subtelomeric ends.

186
00:37:40,270 --> 00:37:43,250
But you see that there is a very,
very distinct cladal structure.

187
00:37:43,450 --> 00:37:45,130
It's not just one big blob.

188
00:37:45,390 --> 00:37:48,110
There are groups of
things that fit together.

189
00:37:48,590 --> 00:37:50,270
There are these sets.

190
00:37:50,390 --> 00:37:52,930
This is the acrocentrics again, and so on.

191
00:37:53,070 --> 00:37:57,570
And to give a little more definition
to this, we decided to use a

192
00:37:57,570 --> 00:38:00,890
community assignment algorithm
that works on top of a graph.

193
00:38:01,070 --> 00:38:04,250
In this case, the graph is actually
defined by the similarity metric

194
00:38:04,250 --> 00:38:04,950
itself.

195
00:38:04,950 --> 00:38:08,150
So there's weighted edges that say,
how similar are my two chromosome,

196
00:38:08,410 --> 00:38:10,570
two subtelomeric PHRs to each other?

197
00:38:10,570 --> 00:38:14,970
And the goal is to maximize the in-group similarity while minimizing the

198
00:38:14,970 --> 00:38:15,710
out-of-group similarity.

199
00:38:16,130 --> 00:38:20,550
And in doing this, we then result in
a set of 15 different communities

200
00:38:21,210 --> 00:38:23,750
that describe the space here.

201
00:38:23,890 --> 00:38:27,010
And you can see that there are still
inter-community relationships in

202
00:38:27,010 --> 00:38:30,810
many cases, but we are kind of maximizing
the amount of inter-community

203
00:38:30,810 --> 00:38:31,510
relationship.

204
00:38:32,570 --> 00:38:33,610
What are some of these?

205
00:38:33,950 --> 00:38:38,090
Just a little taste, because there's
41 of them, so it's very hard to

206
00:38:38,090 --> 00:38:38,790
look at all of them.

207
00:38:39,030 --> 00:38:42,070
On 4q and 10q, there are these
really large repeats of Dux4.

208
00:38:42,270 --> 00:38:47,180
This is known as a relationship
with cancer and oncological

209
00:38:47,180 --> 00:38:47,880
development.

210
00:38:48,240 --> 00:38:50,140
And you can see these repeats here.

211
00:38:51,940 --> 00:38:56,840
There's these tubulin genes
that are at the end of 10p

212
00:38:56,840 --> 00:38:57,580
and 18p.

213
00:38:58,610 --> 00:39:01,230
See this repeat structure there,
