00:39:48,620 --> 00:39:51,140
And this is in maize, so it's not human.

229
00:39:51,220 --> 00:39:53,100
These are the telomeres,
centromeres, and DNA.

230
00:39:53,760 --> 00:39:55,940
This is another view of
it, the zygotene here.

231
00:39:56,200 --> 00:40:00,420
The telomeres are labeled in red, a
little hard to see, because I guess

232
00:40:00,420 --> 00:40:01,360
they're overlapping the green.

233
00:40:01,680 --> 00:40:04,220
This is the cohesin structure
that's being labeled.

234
00:40:04,600 --> 00:40:09,100
And then this bouquet, it dissolves
a bit in pachytene, but you still

235
00:40:09,100 --> 00:40:13,300
have this anchoring on the nuclear
envelope during recombination.

236
00:40:13,500 --> 00:40:18,480
So you have the opportunity for
recombination here, because you're

237
00:40:18,480 --> 00:40:23,180
proximal, you're forced to be on
this manifold, and the sequences are

238
00:40:23,180 --> 00:40:23,940
homologous.

239
00:40:24,080 --> 00:40:27,440
And because you're physically in a
similar place, there's the opportunity

240
00:40:27,440 --> 00:40:30,120
for common function to be
maintained and developed.

241
00:40:32,020 --> 00:40:35,420
And so then we thought we'd make this
a little more quantitative in the

242
00:40:35,420 --> 00:40:39,180
sense of actual 3D organization of
the cell, and so we went to Hi-C

243
00:40:39,180 --> 00:40:39,880
data.

244
00:40:39,920 --> 00:40:41,620
This is kind of crazy.

245
00:40:41,620 --> 00:40:44,700
It's like a repetition of the whole
project just on mouse in order to

246
00:40:44,700 --> 00:40:45,400
see this.

247
00:40:45,400 --> 00:40:49,140
So we built the PHRs from scratch,
and then we're looking at

248
00:40:49,140 --> 00:40:51,060
the Jaccard similarity.

249
00:40:51,460 --> 00:40:55,700
So it's a metric of sequence similarity
versus physical distance implied

250
00:40:55,700 --> 00:40:58,420
by the contact rate.

251
00:40:58,620 --> 00:41:01,040
And you can see that there is
this quite strong correlation.

252
00:41:01,260 --> 00:41:06,160
Once you get above zero similarity,
when you start to share,

253
00:41:06,300 --> 00:41:08,100
then you see this kind of trend.

254
00:41:08,200 --> 00:41:11,900
And also that this is amplified
in the bouquet stage.

255
00:41:12,100 --> 00:41:13,500
So it makes perfect sense.

256
00:41:14,300 --> 00:41:15,140
So it's in mouse.

257
00:41:15,240 --> 00:41:16,800
But then we also did it
in human, of course.

258
00:41:17,260 --> 00:41:21,860
So here we have effectively
observing the same thing.

259
00:41:21,940 --> 00:41:22,640
This is with Pore-C.

260
00:41:22,720 --> 00:41:27,400
So it's kind of multi-fragment
Hi-C and maps very well to these

261
00:41:27,400 --> 00:41:28,100
regions.

262
00:41:28,380 --> 00:41:31,440
And we also have the same thing
in regular Hi-C on CHM13.

263
00:41:34,450 --> 00:41:36,990
And this does also match
our community assignment.

264
00:41:37,250 --> 00:41:40,770
So we see some structure that matches
the communities we've assigned.

265
00:41:41,010 --> 00:41:44,710
And you can, I think, appreciate
that inside of these communities you

266
00:41:44,710 --> 00:41:48,710
have a slightly stronger rate
of contact than outside of it.

267
00:41:50,000 --> 00:41:54,940
And so finally, just to close,
we did attempt to see if

268
00:41:54,940 --> 00:41:55,920
we could catch this in the act.

269
00:41:56,060 --> 00:41:59,400
And by looking at a multi-generational pedigree from WashU,

270
00:42:00,650 --> 00:42:04,830
this plot is showing us
effectively untangling.

271
00:42:04,970 --> 00:42:09,830
So we built a graph of
a child and actually

272
00:42:09,830 --> 00:42:11,050
their mother's haplotypes.

273
00:42:11,830 --> 00:42:16,510
And in the maternal haplotype,
we're asking, which one of

274
00:42:16,510 --> 00:42:19,770
the mother's haplotypes are we seeing?

275
00:42:19,870 --> 00:42:21,870
So we're effectively trying
to measure recombination.

276
00:42:22,410 --> 00:42:25,430
And so you have haplotype 1
and haplotype 2 of the mother.

277
00:42:25,610 --> 00:42:30,250
And this is showing how would I
reconstruct the haplotypes of the child

278
00:42:30,250 --> 00:42:31,510
relative to those of the mother.

279
00:42:31,630 --> 00:42:32,710
That's effectively what's going on.

280
00:42:32,870 --> 00:42:34,870
So many of them, there's no recombinant.

281
00:42:34,970 --> 00:42:35,970
You just have a single chunk.

282
00:42:36,310 --> 00:42:39,790
But we see some kind of tantalizing
signals, like, for example, here,

283
00:42:39,970 --> 00:42:41,290
which I'll zoom in on,

284
00:42:42,010 --> 00:42:46,410
that where you have what looks like
ongoing gene conversion between

285
00:42:46,410 --> 00:42:48,830
9p and 3p.

286
00:42:49,370 --> 00:42:52,570
And this matches also the
community patterns we see.

287
00:42:52,770 --> 00:42:56,730
So we think this is some
positive evidence for this.

288
00:42:56,890 --> 00:42:59,990
But I wouldn't say it's conclusive,
because unfortunately, when you look

289
00:42:59,990 --> 00:43:02,390
at much worse quality assemblies,
you see a lot more of this.

290
00:43:03,670 --> 00:43:08,310
So it is compatible, but maybe
not definitive proof of an actual

291
00:43:08,310 --> 00:43:09,030
recombination event.

292
00:43:09,250 --> 00:43:12,390
But it would make a lot of sense,
I think, that you have many gene

293
00:43:12,390 --> 00:43:15,410
conversion events in regions that
are physically close to each other

294
00:43:15,410 --> 00:43:17,010
during recombination.

295
00:43:18,040 --> 00:43:22,790
And so in conclusion, there
are pseudo-homologous

296
00:43:22,790 --> 00:43:26,730
sub-telomeric regions that are the
near ubiquitous feature of human sub-

297
00:43:26,730 --> 00:43:27,430
telomeres.

298
00:43:28,410 --> 00:43:31,910
For lack of time, I didn't talk about
the backstory behind this, but we

299
00:43:31,910 --> 00:43:34,810
have a lot of evidence over the years,
starting in the early 2000s and

300
00:43:34,810 --> 00:43:37,770
with cytogenetics, that this is a thing.

301
00:43:37,790 --> 00:43:42,290
But this is the first opportunity we
had to systematically observe it at

302
00:43:42,290 --> 00:43:43,550
a population scale.

303
00:43:43,750 --> 00:43:44,450
In humans.

304
00:43:44,450 --> 00:43:49,190
And they cover around 3.5 megabase
pairs, excluding the acrocentrics

305
00:43:49,190 --> 00:43:50,890
and the PARs on X and Y.

306
00:43:51,050 --> 00:43:54,410
And so this is not an insignificant
part of the human genome.

307
00:43:55,390 --> 00:43:59,350
We see that sequence homology mirrors
physical proximity in a nuclear

308
00:43:59,350 --> 00:44:01,770
organization, which I think
is really fascinating.

309
00:44:01,990 --> 00:44:04,410
And I wonder why, actually.

310
00:44:04,550 --> 00:44:07,090
It's a chicken or egg question.

311
00:44:07,210 --> 00:44:10,790
Is it that the sequence homology
is actually driving the physical

312
00:44:10,790 --> 00:44:14,810
proximity, or is it the homology
just a result of the fact that the

313
00:44:14,810 --> 00:44:16,690
proximity is there?

314
00:44:17,690 --> 00:44:21,990
And as you just saw, a completely
assembled human pedigree suggests that

315
00:44:21,990 --> 00:44:25,230
there may be ongoing and frequent
recombination exchange in these regions.

316
00:44:26,250 --> 00:44:29,050
So with that, I'd like to
